834. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Ovid MEDLINE(R) <2018>
ID  - 28874103
T1  - Neuroendocrine Regulation of Food Intake in Polycystic Ovary Syndrome.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1177/1933719117728803
A1  - Romualdi, Daniela
A1  - Immediata, Valentina
A1  - De Cicco, Simona
A1  - Tagliaferri, Valeria
A1  - Lanzone, Antonio
Y1  - 2018//
Y2  - 20170906//
N2  - Several peripheral and central signals are involved in the sophisticated regulation of food intake. Women with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) are prone to consume a diet higher in saturated fat and foods with high glycemic index and show impaired appetite regulation and measures of satiety. As a consequence, obesity, mostly of the central type, is prevalent in the syndrome and worsens the endocrine and metabolic profile of the affected patients. This review article briefly analyzes the current knowledge about the neuroendocrine mechanisms underlying the interplay between feeding behavior, obesity, and reproductive abnormalities in PCOS.
